tudents from receiving a portion of the benefit to which they are entitled. &#10;If the formula for funding is properly structured, no one can &quot;hijack&quot; anything, and no one loses benefits. Again, if my state can do it, so can others. &#10;Further, if you want to use a service, you have the option to do so. Enroll in the school that you wish for your child to attend, such that the state makes provisions for you to use their services. &#10;My state allows homeschooled students to enroll for just one class, or more, or to participate in just one club or sport, or more. They provide the funding for that. We don't have to enroll as full-time students. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="950" language="en" documentId="663" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="KRAMV" date="09/06/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=38" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="663" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="383"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="384" end="537"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="538" end="736"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="737" end="950"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>